\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

Generative models are a class of machine learning models that are used to generate new data samples that are similar to a given set of training data. These models are widely used in a variety of applications, including image synthesis, data augmentation, and image editing. In recent years, deep learning techniques have revolutionized the field of generative modeling, and several powerful generative models have been proposed, including the variational autoencoder (VAE) \cite{kingma2013auto}, the generative adversarial network (GAN) \cite{goodfellow2014generative}, and the deep convolutional generative adversarial network (DCGAN) \cite{radford2015unsupervised}.

The VAE is a popular generative model that uses a probabilistic approach to model the data distribution. It consists of two neural networks: a decoder network that maps a latent code to an image, and an encoder network that maps an image to a latent code. The model is trained to maximize the likelihood of the data, while also learning a generative model that can be used to synthesize new images. However, the VAE has several limitations, including the difficulty in training and the inability to generate high-quality images.

The GAN is another popular generative model that uses a competitive approach to model the data distribution. It consists of two neural networks: a generator network that generates images, and a discriminator network that distinguishes between real and fake images. The model is trained to maximize the likelihood of the data, while simultaneously learning to fool the discriminator. However, the GAN has several limitations, including the difficulty in training and the tendency to generate images that are not visually similar to the training data.

The DCGAN is a variant of the GAN that uses a deep convolutional neural network architecture for both the generator and the discriminator. It has been shown to be more effective than the GAN in generating high-quality images, but it still has several limitations, including the difficulty in training and the tendency to generate images that are not visually similar to the training data.

In this paper, we propose a new generative model called the variational generative adversarial network (VGAN) that addresses the limitations of the existing generative models. The proposed model is based on a novel formulation of the VAE, which we call the \emph{variational generative adversarial network} (VGAN). The proposed model is trained to maximize the likelihood of the data, while simultaneously learning a generative model that can be used to synthesize new images. We have shown that the proposed model outperforms the existing generative models on several benchmark datasets, and we have also demonstrated its ability to generate high-quality images that are visually similar to the training data.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows. In Section \ref{sec:related_work}, we review the related work in the field of generative modeling. In Section \ref{sec:vgan}, we introduce the proposed VGAN model, and in Section \ref{sec:experiments} we evaluate the proposed model on several benchmark datasets. Finally, in Section \ref{sec:conclusion} we conclude the paper and discuss future directions for research.

